# Cursor Rules for React Application

## Tech Stack Conventions
- React + Vite
- TanStack (Router, Query, Form)
- Chakra UI v3
- Zod
- Zustand

## File Structure
- Features-based folder structure
- `src/`
  - `features/` - Feature-based modules
  - `shared/` - Shared components, hooks, and utilities
  - `api/` - API integration layer
  - `store/` - Zustand store definitions
  - `types/` - TypeScript type definitions
  - `constants/` - Application constants
  - `utils/` - Utility functions

## Naming Conventions
- Components: PascalCase (e.g., `UserProfile.tsx`)
- Files: PascalCase for components, camelCase for others
- Hooks: camelCase prefixed with 'use' (e.g., `useAuthenticationState`)
- Types/Interfaces: PascalCase with descriptive names
- Store slices: camelCase suffixed with 'Store' (e.g., `userProfileStore`)

## TypeScript
- Enable strict mode
- Use type inference where possible
- Prefer interfaces for object definitions
- Use generics for reusable components/functions
- Use discriminated unions for complex state management
- Utilize const assertions for literal types
- Use `satisfies` operator for type validation

## Components
- Prefer functional components
- Use type-safe props with interfaces
- Implement error boundaries at feature level
- Extract complex logic into custom hooks
- Keep components focused and single-responsibility
- Use composition over inheritance

## State Management (Zustand)
- Define typed store slices
- Use immer for immutable updates
- Implement selectors for derived state
- Keep stores minimal and focused

## Data Fetching (TanStack Query)
- Define type-safe query hooks
- Implement proper error handling
- Use suspense mode where appropriate
- Define retry and cache policies

## Forms (TanStack Form)
- Use Zod schemas for validation
- Type form values using schema inference
- Implement controlled inputs
- Handle submission states properly

## Styling (Chakra UI)
- Use theme tokens consistently
- Implement responsive designs
- Create reusable style configurations
- Use semantic color modes

## Code Quality
- No explicit `any` types
- No unused variables or imports
- Meaningful variable names (avoid abbreviations)
- Proper error handling with typed errors
- Use early returns for cleaner code
- Implement proper loading states
- Use TypeScript assertion functions where needed

## Comments
- Only document complex business logic
- Use JSDoc for public APIs
- Avoid obvious comments
- Document workarounds and technical debt

## Testing
- Write unit tests for utilities
- Component testing with proper setup
- Mock external dependencies
- Test error scenarios
- Use strong typing in tests

## Performance
- Implement proper memoization
- Use virtual lists for large datasets
- Optimize bundle size
- Implement code splitting
- Use proper key props in lists

## Error Handling
- Create typed error boundaries
- Use custom error types
- Implement proper fallbacks
- Log errors appropriately

## API Integration
- Type all API responses
- Implement proper error handling
- Use proper status codes
- Handle loading states